        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to obtain the previously unobserved sub-mm emission line H21alpha from highly excited hydrogen (transition n=22 to 21) at 0.4525 mm, 662.52 GHz (band 9), for a prototypical hypergiant Zeta-1 Sco (B1.5 Ia+).

Requested Sensitivity: 
The continuum emission flux density of Zeta-1 Sco at 662.52 GHz is expected to be about 47mJy. Our simulation showed that at 57.5mJy the peak of the emission line is predicted to lie roughly 23% above this continuum (see Fig. 1 of the proposal). We  request a channel-to-channel sensitivity of 1.5 mJy, which will allow us to observe the hydrogen line above the continuum with more than 7-sigma level. We would like to observe in dual polarization, to have a better sensitivity.

Correlator setup: 
Zeta-1 Sco has a wind terminal velocity of v_inf=390 km/s. At 662.52 GHz this corresponds to a spectral width of 1723 MHz. We therefore would like to observe the spectral line with the widest available bandwidth for each baseband, 2000 MHz. As we do not expect much variations in the line, a resolution of 31.25 MHz is sufficient. 
Three basebands will be centred at rest frequencies 660.77, 662.52 664.25 GHz to allow the coverage of the continuum and the line, with some overlap at the baseband edges. 
By centering a baseband at the hydrogen line frequency of 662.52 GHz, the spectral setup will allow the observation of the line with the continuum observed for about 138MHz on each side of that baseband. The two basebands placed on either sides of the line will be centred at 660.77 and 664.25 GHz and will cover mostly the continuum and a small part of the line. The fourth baseband will be centred at the same 662.52 GHz for redundancy purposes, in case bad channels affected some basebands.

Imaging requirements: 
The H21alpha line arising from massive OB stars is formed close to the star, and we can consider that the sources are point sources. Therefore, no special imaging is required, and the observation can be carried out in any configuration.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
