    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Evidence points to the presence of clumping in the wind of massive OB stars, leading to downward revisions of the mass-loss (ms) rates. Such revisions would have enormous implications on our understanding of massive-star evolution. It is needed to establish the true ms rates of OB stars separated from the effect of clumping. Unfortunately, current ms diagnostics in the FUV, IR and radio regimes are subject to the uncertainties due to clumping.
The winds in sub-mm zone is extremely sensitive to clumping. Our simulations predict considerable sub-mm emission from highly excited hydrogen H21alpha (n=22 to 21) at 662.52GHz, never observed in massive OB stars before.

We propose to observe this line on Zeta-1 Sco (B1.5 Ia+) to:
1. enlarge available information by this feature which shape and strength is unknown so far;
2. model the observed line to derive an independent estimate of ms rates, to be compared with data from other wavelength region and tighten our constrain of wind clumping;
3. compare the observed and predicted line shape for a detailed check of our atmospheric models and radiative transfer methods, as well as for the accuracy of our atomic model for hydrogen.</prp:abstract>
